      "note_no": "256",
      "note": "Lit., \"make them incline towards thee\" (Zamakhshari; see also Lane IV, 1744)."
    },
    {
      "note_no": "257",
      "note": "My rendering of the above parable is based on the primary meaning of the imperative surhunna ilayka (\"make them incline towards thee\", i.e., \"teach them to obey thee\"). The moral of this story has been pointed out convincingly by the famous commentator Abu Muslim (as quoted by Razi): \"If man is able - as he undoubtedly is - to train birds in such a way as to make them obey his call, then it is obvious that God, whose will all things obey, can call life into being by simply decreeing, 'Be!'\""
